WHY USE REDIRECT?
- You can save the messages to a file instead of displaying the output on the terminal. 
Alternatively, you can use redirection to discard output or errors, so they are not displayed
on the terminal or saved.
- You can redirect a process stdout to suppress the process output from appearing on the terminal.
If you redirect stdout to a file and the file does not exist, then the file is created. If the file
does exist and the redirection does not append (add) to the file, then the redirection overwrites the file's
contents. To discard the output of a process, you can redirect to the empty /dev/null special file that
discards channel output that is redirected to it.

stdin – standard input 
stdout – standard output 
stderr – standard error 

0 - standard input
1 - standard output
2 - standard error

ls > text.txt - list in text.txt file
date > /tmp/saved-timestampt - save current date to /tmp/saved-timestamp
tail -n 100 /var/log/secure > /tmp/last-100-log-secure - save 100 lines from below from /var/log/secure to /tmp/last-100-log-secure 
cat step1.sh step2.log step3 step4 > /tmp/all-four-steps-in-one - display all the content of this file in /tmp/all-four-steps-in-one

